column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE SPOTTING TANK CAR AT CUSTOMERS RAIL SIDING, TRAIN CREW OBSERVED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET. TRAIN DISPATCHER AND CUSTOMER NOTIFIED. RESPONSE INSPECTION SHOWED PRODUCT WEEPING THROUGH THREADS AT BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED USING LARGE WRENCH. AREA WAS CLEANED AND OBSERVED. NO FURTHER LOSS OF PRODUCT DETECTED. TANK CAR HAS TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. INTERNAL VALVE NEEDS TO BE INSPECTED BEFORE RELOADING TANK CAR SHIPPER NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: TRAILER ARRIVED AT XWW FROM LINE HAUL RUN (XHG). WHEN DOOR WAS OPENED DSR NOTICED DARK BROWN LIQUID ON FLOOR-SLIGHT ODOR. IMMEDIATELY CLOSED DOOR AND PULLED TRAILER TO YARD. CHECKED COSO AND DETERMINED H/M WAS LEAKING IN NOSE OF TRAILER. CALLED EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AND SAFETY SUPERVISOR. CALLED PETROCLEAN TO CLEAN UP TRAILER. DSR NOTICED  WET AREA ON FRONT CORNER OF TRAILER- PUT RECOVERY DRUM WITH FLOOR DRY IN IT AT BOTH CORNERS UNDER FRONT OF TRAILER IN CASE OF DRIPPING. SHIPPER PROVIDED MSDS SHEETS AND PETROCLEAN CLEANED AREA AND REMOVED CONTAMINATED MATERIALS. GOOD MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN NEW RECOVERY DRUM AND SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
UPON ARRIVAL A STRONG ODOR WAS BEING RELEASED FROM CARGO COMPARTMENT. FOUND UNDECLARED  HOSE. AIRCRAFT WAS CHECKED AND NO PRODUCT WAS FOUND IN BERRY. AIRCRAFT WAS RELEASED AND PUT BACK INTO SERVICE.
column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: DRUM WAS SITTING ON DOCK. FOS NOTICED SMALL AMOUNT OF FLUID NEAR DRUM. AFTER INSPECTING FREIGHT A SLOW LEAK WAS DISCOVERED ON BOTTOM OF DRUM.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: WHEN TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED TWO CONTAINERS OF RMW FELL OVER. THE LOAD WAS NOT  STACKED OR SECURED VERY WELL. CUSTOMER REMINDED TO LOAD TRAILER BETTER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: US POSTAL SHIPMENT LEAKED. CHAIN SAW HAD BEEN PLACED IN BOX WITH GASOLINE STILL IN CHAIN SAW. MAIL SHIPMENT ORIGINATED IN PINVILLE. LEAK OF GASOLINE WAS DETECTED ON FLIGHT # 3595 DFW TO LIT. GASOLINE VAPORS DETECTED BY PILOTS AND FLIGHT ATTENDANT. CREW WORE MASKS FOR OXYGEN WHILE SEARCHING CARGO HOLD FOR SOURCE OF VAPORS. CAPTAIN PLACED BOX CONTAINING CHAIN SAW IN PLASTIC BAG. FLIGHT DIVERTED TO TXK AT 18:40 PM. TXK CRASH FIRE & RESCUE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TOOK PHOTOGRAPHS & VIDEO AND IMPOUNDED THE CHAIN SAW. AIRCRAFT # 548 AT (ATR) WAS SERVICED INSPECTED AND RELEASED BY MAINTENANCE. PASSENGERS WERE PICKED UP BY LATER FLIGHT TO LIT. NO INJURIES.

WHILE REMOVING A SPOOL FROM A TRAILER THE FORKLIFT BLADES CAUGHT THE FRONT OF THE SKID CONTAINING THE DRUMS WHICH WERE NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED, BRACED OR SECURED FELL OVER. THE BUNG CAPS HAD A SAFETY VALVE ON THEM THAT OPENED CAUSING THE LOSS OF 20 GALLONS OF FLUID. REMTECH ENGINEERING WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY REMTECH. ALL WASTE ITEMS WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUMS FOR LATER DISPOSAL.

SHIPMENT PLACED ON TOP OF OTHER FREIGHT WITHOUT BEING BLOCKED OR BRACED. DURING TRANSIT CONTAINER FELL STRIKING ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT WHICH CAUSED THE SPILL. THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE. PROPER UTILIZATION OF PROPER BLOCKING, BRACING AND DUNNAGE WOULD OF PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT FORM OCCURRING.

WEARING FULL P.P.E. I WAS NOTIFIED TO RESPONDED TO WET PKG FRONT END, PKG WAS WET NOT LEAKING. FOLLOWING DELINE STRIPS OF THE DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEETS FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID I PLACED CORROSIVE IN SPILL PUT AND PROCESSED IN MY DESIGNATED AREA.

RESPONDED TO CALL ON WILMINGTON SLIDE WEARING ALL PROPER PPE. SAW CORROSIVE LABEL AND USING DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET I PUT THE LEAKER IN TUB, BROUGHT IT BACK TO PSC, AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: RESPONDED TO SPILL USING DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET. ALL SPILLED MATERIALS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND ABSORBED WITH SPEEDY DRY (CLAY ABSORBENT). ALL MATERIALS PROCESSED ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURES. PPE WORN (GLOVES, GOGGLES, APRON AND BOOTS).

column42: ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, NOT LESS THAN 50 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE PURPLE BELT WEARING MY PPE. I REFERRED TO THE DECISION TREE AND TURNED TO THE CORROSIVE LIQUID. RESPONDS SHEET I USED PH AND TESTED IT TO BE 3 USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NUTRALIZE THE MATERIAL AND DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL THROUGH THE DMP AND DECONAMINATED MY PPE AND EQUIPMENT.

column42: ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, NOT LESS THAN 50 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL IN THE METRO 2ND WEARING MY PPE. I REFERRED TO THE DECSION TREE AND TURNED TO THE CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. IPA THE MATERIAL AND IT REG 3 I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NUTRALIZE THE MATERIAL AND RE-PH IT REG 7 I USE CLAY ABSORBENT TO MIX WITH THE MATERIAL. I DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL THROUGH THE DMP AND DECONTAMINATED MY PPE AND EQUIPMENT.

THE SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE WAS COUNSELED IN THE PROPER SHIPPING CONTAINERS FOR THE VARIOUS TYPES OF WASTES.

column168: UNIT WAS SOUTHBOUND ON US 207 OF BORGER TX. DRIVER ENTERED A CURVE AND THE UNIT LEFT THE HIGHWAY. DRIVER OVER STEERED AND THE UNIT ROLLED OVER. AMARILLO HAZ MAT WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. FORTY YARDS OF SOIL WAS EXCAVATED. THE SITE WAS TESTED AND THE SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO A BFI LANDFILL NEAR CANTON, TX.

PATCHES OF LEAKING OIL WERE CLEANED DRUMMED AND DISPOSED OF AS PCB CONTAMINATED DEBRIS. LEAKING TRANSFORMERS WERE WIPED DOWN AND PLACED IN 1/2 BOXES LINED WITH VISQUEEN. ALL MATERIAL WERE THEN TRANSPORTED TO SALES CO. NO CONTAMINATION WAS NOTED ON THE GROUND AROUND THE TRAILER.

column168: AT GENERATOR SITE DURING LOADING PROCESS, DRUMS WERE BEING LOADED BY A FORKLIFT AND ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A PROTRUDING E-TRACK RAIL ON LEFT SIDE OF VAN TRAILER. HAZMAT ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP'S VAN TRAILERS ARE EQUIPPED WITH E- TRACK RAIL SECUREMENT SYSTEM. THE TRAILER WAS PARKED ON A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY THREE (3) GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE DRUM. THE GENERATOR RESPONSE TEAM HANDLED THE CLEAN UP. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND THE TRAILER AND CONTAINMENT PAD WERE DECONTAMINATED. ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS REMAINED AT THE GENERATOR SITE FOR DISPOSAL AT A FUTURE DATE. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND DELIVERED TO THE FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE MANIFEST (ITEM#C). NO MATERIAL ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.

column168: ON THURSDAY, 10/7/99 OUR DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-75 WITH REF#104947 ON BOARD. IN THE NORMAL OPERATION OF HIS TRACTOR TRAILER HE HAD TO REACT QUICKLY TO AVOID A REAR END COLLISION WITH AN AUTOMOBILE AND A CEMENT MIXER TRUCK THAT ABRUPTLY PUT ON THEIR BRAKES. UPON BRAKING HARD, OUR DRIVER FELT THE LOAD SHIFT IN HIS TRUCK. HE PROCEEDED TO THE NEXT EXIT AND INSPECTED HIS LOAD. UPON INSPECTION HE FOUND THAT AT LEAST 10 OF THE 64 BARRELS WERE NOW ON THEIR SIDE. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, HE DISCOVERED THAT FLUID WAS LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE BARRELS. THE COMMODITY WAS SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION (UN#1824). IMMEDIATELY, THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SEEN. BRENT KISER, PUCO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST INSPECTED OUR DRIVER, EQUIPMENT, AND THE SPILL DURING THE COURSE OF HIS INVESTIGATION. I DISPATCHED ENVIRONMENTAL ENTERPRISES, INC. (513-772-2818) TO THE SCENE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND INSPECT THE SHIPMENT. THEY ARRIVED AT 1827 AND ABSORBED THE SPILL AND STOOD UP THE BARRELS THAT HAD TIPPED OVER. THEY COMPLETED THEIR WORK AT 1940 AND CONFIRMED THAT ONLY ONE BARREL HAD LEAKED. THE LEAKING BARREL HAD A LOOSE BUNG THAT TOOK ONE FULL TURN TO BE SECURED. IN ADDITION, TWO OTHER UPRIGHT BARRELS WERE FOUND TO HAVE LOOSE BUNGS. SUBSEQUENTLY, THE LOAD WAS SECURED AS MUCH AS WAS POSSIBLE AND RELEASED BY BRENT KISER FOR DELIVERY.I INTERVIEWED OUR DRIVER AND SECURED HIS WRITTEN STATEMENT ON THE COURSE OF EVENTS. IN ADDITION, I TOOK PICTURES TO DOCUMENT THE SCENE AND CONDITION OF THE LOAD. IN MY VIEW, THE LOAD WAS NOT LOADED OR PACKED PROPERLY BY THE SHIPPER. THERE WERE TWO TYPES OF UN#1824. THIRTY-TWO BARRELS @ 680# EACH, AND THIRTY-TWO @ 700# EACH. THEY WERE PACKED FOUR TO A SKID WITH ONE NYLON-BANDING STRAP AROUND THEM AT THE TOP. THIS WAS NOT ENOUGH TO HOLD 2720# TO 2800# SAFETY INTACT IN NORMAL TRANSPORT. A DUNNAGE OR CARDBOARD CORNER WITH ADDITIONAL BANDING IS NEEDED. THE FREIGHT WAS SAFELY DELIVERED ON FRIDAY, 10/8/99. UPON OFFLOADING OUR DRIVER SAID HE DISCOVERED ADDITIONAL BARRELS WITH LOOSE BUNGS. IF THE BUNGS ON THE BARRELS WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND THE SKIDS PACKED TIGHTLY WITH DUNNAGE AND BANDING THIS INCIDENT WOULD NEVER HAD OCCURRED. I FIND NO LIABILITY ON RUSH TRANSPORTATION/LOGISTICS PART. THEREFORE, WE WILL INVOICE SOUTHSIDE SERVICES FOR ANY AND ALL EXPENSES WE INCURRED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND OUR TRAILER. I HAVE ATTACHED COPIES OF THE PUCO REPORT AND OUR DRIVER'S STATEMENT FOR YOUR RESPECTIVE REVIEW.

column168: ABOUT 19:15, IN THE AREA OF OPELOUSAS, LA. WHILE ON THE ROAD, THE TANKER PRESSURE HAD BEGUN TO INCREASE, AND THE DRIVERS DECIDED THAT A VENTING WAS NECESSARY. THEY DROVE TO A NEARBY CUSTOMER LOCATION (LOUANNA FOODS) WHERE THEY PERFORMED A BRIEF, CONTROLLED VENTING, DROPPING PRESSURE FROM 26 TO 13 PSI. AFTERWARD, THEY RETURNED TO THE INTERSTATE AND CONTINUED THE TRIP TO NEW ORLEANS.

A LIQUID HYDROGEN TANKER WAS ON THE RETURN TRIP TO THE NEW ORLEANS FACILITY AFTER MAKING A DELIVERY. THE TANKER WAS EMPTY. HOWEVER WHILE ON THE ROAD THE DRIVERS NOTICED A CONTINUING ELEVATED PRESSURE. TO AVOID THE POSSIBILITY OF HAVING THE SAFETY VENTS OPEN WHILE TRAVELING ON THE ROAD, THEY DECIDED IT WAS NECESSARY TO PULL OFF THE ROAD AND PERFORM A CONTROLLED, MANUAL VENTING OF THE TRAILER. NOT HAVING A CUSTOMER "SAFE HAVEN" WITHIN THE IMMEDIATE AREA, AND AFTER SEEING A 47 TO 51 PSI INCREASE WITHIN 10 MINUTES, THEY DECIDED TO MAKE A CONTROLLED VENTING ALONGSIDE AN ISOLATED SECTION OF THE INTERSTATE. THIS OCCURED IN THE AREA OF I-49, EXIT 162. THE DRIVERS FOLLOWED THEIR STANDARD VENTING SAFETY PROTOCOL, AND AFTER APPROX 3 MINUTES OF VENTING, THE TANKER PRESSURE DROPPED TO AN ACCEPTABLE 13 PSI. AFTER WAITING APPROX 60 MINUTES, AND NOTING NO SIGNIFICANT PRESSURE INCREASES, THE DRIVERS RETURNED TO THE INTERSTATE  AND CONTINUED DRIVING SOUTH TO NEW ORLEANS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VET'S OIL CO. BULK TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT. OUR BULK TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WEST ON BAILEY ST AND WAS STRUCK BY A PICK UP TRAVELING NORTH ON 4TH ST CAUSING OUR TRUCK TO TIP OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE CAUSING SPILLAGE OF CONTENTS IN RIGHT SIDE COMPARTMENT. THE BULK TANK AND CONTENTS WERE IN TACT AND NO SPILLAGE OCCURED. THE PICK UP EXPERIENCED DAMAGED TO THE HOOD AREA AND APPROX 40,000 DAMAG WAS DONE TO OUR POWER UNIT. IN THE POLICE REPORT THE DRIVER OF THE PICK UP STATED HIS PASSENGER WINDOW WAS DUSTY AND DIDN't SEE OUR BULK TRUCK UNTILL IMPACT. THE PICK UP RAN HIS YIELD SIGN. THE DRIVER OF THE PICK UP WAS CITED FOR FAILURE TO YIELD. THE JACKSON POLICE DEPT AND JACKSON FIRE DEPT ASSISTED. A MN DOT OFFICER WAS ON THE SCENE AS WAS A MN POLLUTION CONTROL AGENT. AS PRECAUTION WATER WAS RUN THROUGH THE STORM SEWER. BOTH THE DOT OFFICER AND THE MPCA AGENT WAS SATISFIED WITH CLEAN UP AND CONDITION OF THE TRUCK AFTER THEIR RESPECTIVE INVESTIGATIONS.

column168: DODX 14326 A RESIDUE TANK CAR OF AVIATION FUEL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT THE CSXT YARD IN ROCKY MOUNT, NC ON OCTOBER 15,1999. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND PADS WERE PLACED UNDER THE OUTLET BY YARD PERSONNEL. A CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE YARD AND FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPEN AND THE CAP LOOSE. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE CAR WAS SHIPPED. THE PRODUCT SPILL AND PADS WERE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

GATX 70206 FOUND IN YARD WITH WETNESS ON SIDES OF TANK AND A STRONG ODOR. CAR ISOLATED. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER, ARIZONA CHEM, OK CSXT HAZMAT TO CALL AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO REPAIR CAR. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. A COUPLE WERE ONLY HAND TIGHT. A NEW MANWAY GASKET WAS IN PLACE BUT IT LOOKED LIKE IT HAD NOT BEEN COMPRESSED ALL THE WAY AROUND. THEY CLEANED THE LIP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE, REINSTALLED THE GASKET AND SECURED THE MANWAY BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT. THEY ALSO FOUND THE LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS NOT HAND TIGHT. THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE FROM THE VALVE. THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT ANY PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE GROUND.

A VAN TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AT 0920 ON OCTOBER 15,1999. THE TRAILER WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 167 AT MILE 18.5 IN KENT, WA. THE CITY OF KENT FIRE DEPARTMENT, WASHINGTON STATE PATROL, WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY RESPONDED TO THE EVENT. THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS IDENTIFIED. REPRESENTATIVES FROM PHILIP SERVICES CORP.   RESPONDED WITH A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS OVERAPCKED AND THE SPILLED MATERAIL WAS RECOVERED. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS A RESULT OF A LOAD LOCK FAILURE AND LOAD SHIFTING. THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS A 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WHICH SPILT AT THE SEAM WHEN THE LOAD SHIFTED.THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND PLACED IN DRUMS FOR TRANSPORTATION TO A DISPOSAL FACILITY. THE SPILL WAS DETERMINED TO BE REPORTABLE AND THE NRC STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMITTEE, LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMITTEE AND WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY WERE CONTACTED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A LEAKING 55 GALLON DRUM WAS NOTICED IN THE WAREHOUSE DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION. APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF WASTE HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO THE FLOOR IN THE WAREHOUSE. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT PADS AND VERMICULITE. THIS SPILL GENERATED TWO POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET DOLTON IL FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE WAREHOUSE WERE COUNSELED IN THE PROPER HANDLING AND STORAGE OF WASTE DRUMS.

A SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE DROPPED A 55 GALLON DRUM WHILE UNLOADING IT FROM HIS VEHICLE. THE LID OF THE DRUM WAS CRACKED OPEN WHEN IT STRUCK THE GROUND ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF WASTE TO SPILL INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACKS. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 600 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DR SE HEBRON OH FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS BRIEF TO USE MORE CARE WHILE LOADING DRUMS ONTO HIS VEHICLE.

AT THIS FACILITY A TRAILER WAS BEING MOVED TO BE UNLOADED WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF WASTE HAD LEAKED ONTO THE ASPHALT. THE TRAILER WAS MOVED INTO THE DOCK AREAR TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER SPILL.THE TRAILER WAS OPENED AND 3X55 GALLON DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING. THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT. THE DRUMS WERE ENROUTE TO THE FACILITY AT WHICH THE SPILL OCCURED AT 6125 NORTH PECATONICA ROAD, PECATONIA, IL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 300 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE. THIS SPILL MATERIAL WILL BE CONTAINERIZED FOR DISPOSAL AT THIS FACILITY. THE SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS SPILL REVIEWED THE POLICIES FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING DRUMS WITH HIS SUPERVISOR IN ORDER TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCES.

DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF DRUMS IN THE WAREHOUSE A PINHOLE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED IN A 55 GALLON DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL CLEANED WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD. THIS INCIDENT CREATED APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL DRUM TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 2815 OLD GREENBREIR, TN FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL.THE WAREHOUSE SUPERVISOR WAS COUNSELED TO CLOSELY WATCH THE CONDITION OF THE DRUMS THAT ARE STORED IN THE WAREHOUSE.

AN EMPLOYEE AT THE FACILITY WAS MOVING A 55 GALLON DRUM WITH A FORKLIFT AND DRUM PICKER. THE DRUM SLIPPED OUT OF THE DRUM PICKER AND WAS PUNCTURED BY THE FORKS OF THE FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF LIQUID LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF WASTE THAT WAS ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT 2815 OLD GREENBREIR, TN FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL.THE EMPLOYEE WAS BRIEFED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING DRUMS.

WHILE LOADING A 16 GALLON DRUM OF SOLVENT ONTO A VEHICLE, 1/2 GALLON OF WASTE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE WHEN THE DRUM WAS DROPPED. THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS WHICH WERE PLACED IN A CONTAINER FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL.THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY AT ROUTE 24 3 MILES EAST OF VINTONN AT O'NEAL DRIVEIN VINTON, VA FOR RECYCLING/DISPOSAL.THE DRIVER WAS BRIEFED IN THE PROCEDURES FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING DRUMS.

THE ENGLEWOOD FIRE DEPARTMENT, LOS ANGELES COUNTY DISPATCHED A HAZMAT TEAM TO VERIFY THE NATURE OF THE CHEMICAL AND CONFIRMED NO RISK TO PUBLIC HEALTH. column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE WET AND GIVING OFF AN ODOR LATE IN THE MORNING AT THE HONOLULU FED EX STATION ON 10/21. NO OTHER PACKAGES WERE AFFECTED BY THE SPILL. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS. THERE WAS A SECOND PACKAGE IN THIS SHIPMENT THAT ALSO HAD NO INDICATION THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THE AIRWAY BILL WAS CHECKED NO FOR ANY DANGEROUS GOODS IN THE PACKAGE SECTION. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AS PER FEDEX POLICY AND I WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THE MSDS INFORMATION DID INDICATED THAT THE FLASH POINT WAS 105 DEGREES FARENHEIT, SO THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THE PACKAGES WERE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION ON 10/25.

THE FREIGHT WAS BAGGED AND PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED I SPOKE TO SA BOB CLATTERBLUCK, MSP FAA. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELING SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLING NOTICED LEAKAGE COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 12 AEROSOL CANS OF SOME TYPE OF FLAMMABLE SOLVENT. THE VALVE STEMS ON TWO OF THE AEROSOLS FAILED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF LIQUID. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE CONTAINER NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA INVESTIGATION. PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT ANDY HUBER FAA IND CAFSO AT 16:55 CST ON 10/27/99.

DURING BD OF CGO 1 OF 46 PCS WAS STACKED ON TOP OF HIGH SKID. WAREHOUSE PERSON ATTEMPTED TO LIFT FROM TOP BUT DUE TO WGT AND LOST CONTROL THIS 1 PC FELL TO GROUND AND PUNCTURED HOLE TO 1 OF 4 INNER BOTTLES TO LEAK.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE AND ODOR WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL AN AIRCRAFT FUEL CELL UNIT. THE UNIT HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY DRAINED OF FUEL BEFORE BEING PACKED. THE UNIT LEAKED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE AVIATION FUEL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE UNIT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT ORIGIN.

THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGES WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO SHIPPER RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

DON GALLAM SERVICE CENTER MANAGER AT CON WAY CENTRAL EXPRESS CALLED CLEAN HARBORS HAZ MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY AND THE KENTUCKY EPA OFFICE. BOONE COUNTY POLICE AND FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED AND BOONE COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT. SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON SIGHT AND CLEANED UP BY CLEAN HARBORS. ALL WASTE WAS TAKEN TO CON WAY CENTRAL EXPRESS, 5289 DUFF DR, CINCINNATI, OH 45246 WAITING FOR DISPOSITION.

THERE WAS NO FREIGHT PRESSING UP AGAINST THE TOTE TO HAVE CAUSED THE DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS WAS LOST. A SPILL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS SENT TO THE SITE TO TRANSFER THE TOTE CONTENTS INTO NEW 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS. THE PRODUCT AND DRUMS EMPTY TOTE WERE THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.

WHILE UNLOADING DRIVER NOTICE WET BOX AND CHECKED, ONE JUG HAD BEEN PUNCTURED & REMOVED AND ANOTHER THAT HAD A LEAK WAS DUMPED AT HOSPITAL.

GALLON JUG TURNED OVER IN TRAILER & STARTED LEAKING CUSTOMER RECEIVED FREIGHT WITH ABOUT 1/2 OF IT LEAKED OUT. HAD MEETING WITH DRIVERS & INFORMED DOCK TO MAKE SURE ALL HAZ. MATERIAL ARE BLOCKED & BRACED.
NO REMARKS.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column168: DRIVER HIT W/FORKLIFT WHILE UNLOADING ON TO THEIR DOCK.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH NOT MORE THAN 51% ACID
column168: DOCK ASSOCIATE WAS TURNING THE FORKLIFT THE BLADE STRUCK THE BOX. THE DOCK ASSOCIATE TOLD THE SUPERVISOR WHAT HAD HAPPENED. THE DOCK ASSOCIATE GOT SOME ABSORBALL, ABOUT 10 CUPS WORTH, PLACED IT ON TOP OF THE LIQUID. HE SWEPT UP THE ABSORBALL, PLACED IT IN A 5 GAL PAIL. HE RECOUPED THE REMAINING PRODUCT AND PLACED THE BOX IN THE HAZ-MAT STORAGE AREA. I TALKED TO THE DOCK ASSOCIATE ABOUT THE INCIDENT. I EXPLAINED TO HIM, THAT WHEN HE OPERATES A FORKLIFT, THAT HE NEEDS TO PAY ATTENTION TO THE SURROUNDING.

TRAILER ARRIVED AT CARRIER'S FACILITY AFTER MAKING PICKUPS. WHEN IT WAS UNLOADED, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND WITH A HORIZONTAL PUNCTURE NEAR ITS BOTTOM. IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN GRAZED BY A FORK DURING LOADING. THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. THE TRAILER WAS SENT TO A CONTRACTOR FOR DECONTAMINATION.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE, THE DRIVER MADE A SUDDEN STOP TO AVOID A COLLISION. ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE, HE FOUND THAT ONE DRUM HAD SLID OFF OF ITS PALLET AND HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL AT THE EDGE OF THE PALLET. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DRUM AND PROVIDED ASSISTANCE IN CLEANING THE TRAILER FLOOR.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: AT SOME POINT DURING TRANSIT, THE PALLET ON WHICH THE DRUM WAS RIDING COLLAPSED. THE SHRINK WRAP WHICH WAS SECURING THE DRUM TO THE PALLET THEN FAILED. THE DRUM WAS THEN FREE TO MOVE ABOUT THE TRAILER. IN DOING SO, WHEN IT STRUCK ANOTHER OBJECT, THE DRUM MATERIAL FLEXED ALLOWING THE ESCAPE OF A MINIMAL QUANTITY OF CONTENTS TO ESCAPE THROUGH A FILL CAP VENT.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT A ROUTINE BREAK THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD AND FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AROUND THE TANK'S MANWAY COVER. HE TIGHTENED THE CLAMP RING AND PLACED AN ABSORBENT BOOM AROUND THE COVER. HE PROCEEDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT AND DELIVERED THE SHIPMENT CLEAR.

AT TIME OF DELIVERY THE DRIVER FOUND THAT ONE CARTON HAD BEEN SHIPPED LOOSE ON TOP OF A SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET OF MIXED OTHER PRODUCTS. THE LOOSE CARTON HAD WORKED ITS WAY OVER THE EDGE OF THE PALLET AND WAS LEANING OVER AT AN ANGLE. LEAKAGE WAS OCCURING FROM A LOOSE CAP ON ONE BOTTLE IN THE CARTON. THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE WET CARTON. THE CARTON WAS UPRIGHTED AND OVERPACED FOR RETURN TO A CARRIER FACILITY. INTERNAL INVESTIGATION DISCLOSED THAT THE LOAD HAD PASSED THROUGH AN INTERMEDIATE FACILITY OF THE CARRIER AT WHICH TIME SOME REWORKING OF THE LOAD TOOK PLACE. THE DAMAGED CARTON HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM ITS SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET AT THAT TIME. EXTRA INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN PROVIDED TO THE INVOLVED PERSONNEL.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK, ONE TANK WAS DISCOVERED DRIPPING AT ITS DISCHARGE VALVE. INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM WHAT WOULD APPEAR TO BE A DEFECTIVE GASKET AT THE POINT OF ATTACHMENT OF THE VALVE TO THE TANK BODY. TANK WAS SECURED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0330 A DOCKWORKER ENTERED THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD A PALLET OF FREIGHT. WHILE HIS FORKS SLID UNDER THE PALLET THEY CONTINUED THROUGH TO THE OTHER SIDE, PIERCING A 55 GALLON DRUM, AS STATED ABOVE. ALL EMPLOYEES WERE TOLD TO EVACUATE THE TRAILER AND THE SURROUNDING AREA. THE TRAILER DOOR WAS CLOSED AND AT THE TIME THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED ALONG WITH A HAZ MAT TEAM.
LOCATION HAS DEFECTIVE OIL GUAGE.
WHEN THE SPILL ACCURED WE CLEARED THE AREA THEN WE PROCEDED TO PLACE THE ABSORB ON THE SPILLED LIQUID. ONCE CONTAINED WE PLACED THE DRUM AND THE ABSORB INTO A RECONEY DRUM. HERE A VCT.
FORKLIFT BLADES PUNCTURED BOXES WHEN ENTERING PALLET. RETRAINING BE DONE FOR OPERATOR OF FORKLIFT.

column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: THE PRESSURES RELIEF VALVE OPENED ON TOP OF OUR TRAILER AND STARTED RELEASING PRODUCT.  OUR INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE #1 COMPARTMENT HAD BEEN LOADED TO ITS CAPACITY NOT ALLOWING ROOM FROM EXPANSION.  THE #1 COMPARTMENT HAD A HEEL IN IT WHEN IT WAS LOADED AND WAS NOT ACCOUNTED FROM BY THE SHIPPER.  EMPTY WEIGHT TICKETS WILL BE OBTAINED ON ALL DMDS TRAILERS TO ASCERTAIN IF THEY CONTAIN A HEEL OR NOT PRIOR TO RE-DISPATCHING THE TRAILERS ON ADDITIONAL LOADS.

ON OCTOBER 11, 1999, AT 0850 HOURS, CN CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED AN ODOR AND ESCAPING VAPOR SOUND COMING FROM UTLX910909 (RESIDUE-PROPYLENE) WHILE CLOSING AN OPEN HATCH COVER IN THE BATTLE CREEK YARD, BATTLE CREEK, MICHIGAN.  APPROPRIATE AGENCIES NOTIFIED - CN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM FOUND THE VAPOR EDUCATION AND LIQUID VALVES LOOSE.  BOTH VALVES AND VALVE PLUGS TIGHTENED.  LEAK STOPPED AND TANK CAR RETURNED TO SERVICE.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON OCTOBER 14, 1999 AT 0827 HOURS, CN CAR INSPECTOR DISCOVERED AN ODOR OF PROPANE WHILE INSPECTING GATX 61762 (RESIDUE-LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS) IN THE BATTLE CREEK YARD, BATTLE CREEK, MICHIGAN. APPROPRIATE AGENCIES NOTIFIED.  CN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM DETERMINED THE VAPOR EDUCATION VALVE WAS LOOSE.  VALVE TIGHTENED, ODOR/LEAK STOPPED AND TANK CAR RETURNED TO SERVICE.

column168: A TRAIN CREW WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PREPARING A TRAIN FOR DEPARTURE FROM OUR SALAMANCA, NY YARD TO OUR YARD IN BUFFALO, NY. WHILE SWITCHING THEIR TRAIN IN THE CUSTOMARY MANNER THE TRAIN CONDUCTOR OBSERVED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF A TANK CAR. INITIALLY THE MATERIAL WAS THOUGHT TO BE WATER. LATER, AFTER INVESTIGATING IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE ACID FROM THE CAR. AFTER A VISUAL INSPECTION THE CAR WAS CAREFULLY SWITCHED OUT TO AN ISOLATED AREA AND SECURED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION BY OUR THE RAILROAD'S MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE NOT NOTIFIED BECAUSE THE QUANTITY OF MATERIAL RELEASED WAS DETERMINED TO BE MINIMAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AT 1345 HOURS THE FOLLOWING DAY AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR A CERTIFIED REPAIRMAN FROM A LOCAL TANK CAR REPAIR SHOP TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR. HE FOUND THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE, A WORN MANWAY COVER GASKET AND CAR'S RUPTURE DISC BROKEN. THE CAR WAS REPAIRED AND SENT ON TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING. AFTER UNLOADING, THE CAR WAS SENT TO A SHOP FOR ADDITIONAL REPAIRS. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AFTER DISCUSSING SITUATION WITH THE SHIPPER.

IN THE PROCESS OF REMOVING A LD-11 AIRCRAFT PALLET CONTAINING A PORTION OF THE CONSIGNMENT (2 SKIDS EACH CONTAINING 4 EACH 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS) FROM A DOLLY, ONE OF THE PLASTIC DRUMS WAS PUNCTURED. CARGO SERVICE MANAGER KEITH COCHRAN HAS PROVIDED DETAILED INFORMATION (ATTACHED( DESCRIBING HOW THE PALLET WAS INADVERTENTLY DROPPED AGAINST THE LD-7 DOLLY RESULTING IN THE SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE SIDE, IN THE UPPER PORTION, OF THE PLASTIC DRUM.  THE DRUM THAT HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH THE DOLLY WAS INSPECTED IMMEDIATELY AND FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL LEAK. THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT'S HAZMAT TEAM WAS NOTIFIED WE HAD A SPILL..  THE HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY AND WAS PROVIDED WITH THE NECESSARY TECHNICAL INFORMATION WE HAD OBTAINED FROM THE DOCUMENTS AND BY CONTACTING OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (3-E COMPANY). AFTER THE HAZMAT TEAM HAD SECURED THE PLASTIC DRUM AND IT WAS NO LONGER LEAKING.  CONTINENTAL AIRLINES CONTACTED OUR HAZMAT/ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP PROJECT WAS COMPLETED WITHIN A VERY SHORT PERIOD OF TIME.  THE IAH CASFO WAS ADVISED OF THE SPILL THE NEXT DAY, OCTOBER 13, 1999.  IN AN EFFORT TO MINIMIZE THE POSSIBILITY OF SIMILAR OCCURRENCES IN THE FUTURE, THE HOUSTON CARGO FACILITY HAS INCLUDED A REVIEW OF OUR FORKLIFT PROCEDURES IN THEIR SHIFT MEETINGS.  THIS REVIEW INCLUDES SPECIAL EMPHASIS ON THE POTENTIAL DANGERS OF LIFTING CONTAINERS OR OBJECTS THAT EXCEED THE WEIGHT LIMITATION OF THE FORKLIFT UNIT BEING UTILIZED.

IT WAS ALSO NOTICED THAT THERE WAS EVIDENCE OF LEAKING PRODUCT DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR IN THE AREA WHERE THE GASKET APPEARED NOT TO BE PROPERLY PLACED. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO ALL APPROIATE LOCAL AND STATE AGENCIES. SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE CALLED AND THE CONSIGNEE, DUPONT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT MR JIM MADERE OF DUPONT ALONG WITH AN ADDITIONAL TECHNICIAN ARRIVED AND REPLACED THE GASKET. THE REMOVED GASKET APPEARED TO BE DEGRAGATED AS IF NOT TO BE COMPATIBLE WITH THE PRODUCT. THIS WAS EVIDENT BY THE EMULSION OF THE RUBBER WHERE IT HAD MADE CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT. TANK CAR WAS OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT 1500 HOURS.

column168: AN AUTOMOBILE WAS STOPPED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE ROADWAY WITH HALF IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE. ROGER KIRBY OUR DRIVER SLOWED TO MISS THE CAR WHEN THE OCCUPANTS RAN ACROSS THE ROAD AND OUR DRIVER HAD TO CLIP THE FRONT OF THE CAR TO MISS THE OCCUPANTS. ONE OCCUPANT WAS INJURED WHEN HE RAN BACK TO THE VEHICLE. NO DAMAGE WAS DONE TO OUR TUBE TRAILER OR OUR CARGO. THE ONLY DAMAGE WAS TO THE LEFT FRONT TIRE AND FENDER OF OUR TRACTOR. THE OTHER DRIVER WAS CHARGED WITH THE ACCIDENT. OUR TRAILER ONLY HAD RESIDUE LEFT IN IT FROM A DELIVERY THAT THE DRIVER WAS RETURNING FROM. OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TOLL FREE NUMBER ON HIS MOBILE PHONE AND ALSO 911 FOR LOCAL ASSISTANCE. THERE WAS A DENSE FOG THE MORNING OF THE ACCIDENT AND OUR DRIVER AS USING EXTREME CAUTION ON THE ROADWAY. THE ACCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED IF THE OCCUPANTS OF THE VEHICLE WOULD HAVE STAYED IN THEIR VEHICLE AND NOT BEEN ON THE ROADWAY. A DISCUSSION TOOK PLACE AT OUR TERMINAL SAFETY MEETING FOLLOWING THIS ACCIDENT TO USE EXTREME CAUTION DURING LOW VISIBILITY DAYS.

column168: DURING AN ENROUTE CHECK OF THE FREIGHT, DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL HAD COME FROM THE MANWAY COVER OF  ONE TANK.  HE CONTINUED ON TO A NEARBY FACILITY OF THE CARRIER WHERE THE COVER RETAINER WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TANK WIPED CLEAN.  HE WAS THEN ABLE TO CONTINUE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE, THREE BAGS WERE FOUND TO HAVE BEEN TORN AND TAPED.  SOME MATERIAL HAD SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THEM WITH AN EXCEPTION NOTATION AND CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR.

CARRIER'S DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP.  A FORKLIFT OPERATOR AT THAT LOCATION WAS POSITIONING HIS FORKS UNDER A PALLET TO REMOVE IT.  THE FORKS, WHICH WERE LONGER THAN THE PALLET, EXTENDED THROUGH THE PALLET.  THEY CONTACTED THREE DRUMS WHICH WERE LOADED AHEAD OF THE PALLET, PIERCING ONE DRUM AND DENTING TWO OTHERS.  ONE OF THE DENTED DRUMS WAS FOUND TO HAVE A PINHOLE SIZE PUNCTURE IN THE DENT.  THE OTHER DENTED DRUM DID NOT OTHERWISE FALL. THE FREE LIQUID FROM THE PIERCED DRUM EXITED THE TRAILER AND ENTERED A STRIP DRAIN.  TAKING MATERIALS FROM THIS ON BOARD SPILL KIT, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO A LOCATION WHERE THE STRIP DRAIN ENTERS A SEWER LINE, AND BLOCKED THE ENTRANCE TO THE LINE.  HE THEN MOVED HIS VEHICLE TO A REMOTE LOCATION IN THE PARKING LOT TO ALLOW THE TRAILER TO AIR OUT.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AND ADDED ABSORBENTS TO THE SEWER LINE ENTRANCE TO SUPPLEMENT TO DRIVER'S EFFORTS.  SHORTLY AFTER THE ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, A COMMONWEALTH OF MASSACHUSETTS ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICIAL ARRIVED ON LOCATION.  THE OFFICIAL ORDERED EVACUATION OF THE FACILITY UNTIL AIR MONITORING COULD BE COMPLETED.  AS A COURTESY TO THE FACILITY MANAGEMENT, WHO HAVE LIMITED EXPERIENCE IN DEALING WITH SPILLS, THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO PERFORM MITIGATION.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON LOCATION AND SURVEYED THE SITUATION, THEY WERE ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT ALL OF THE SPILLAGE HAD ENTERED AN UNUSED MANHOLE WHICH IS UPSTREAM FROM THE SEWER ENTRANCE.  THEREFORE, NO MATERIAL ENTERED THE SEWER SYSTEM.  THE CONTRACTOR PERFORMED THE WORK NECESSARY TO DECONTAMINATE THE CARRIER'S TRAILER.  DISPOSAL OF ALL WASTES THAT WERE GENERATED HAVE BEEN ARRANGED FOR BY THE CONTRACTOR.  THE DAMAGED PACKAGES OF PRODUCT HAVE BEEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

AT TIME OF DELIVERY ONE BAG WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THROUGH A TAPED OVER TEAR.  CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED DELIVERY WITH AN EXCEPTION NOTATION.  NO PRODUCT WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER SO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY.

column168: THE DRIVER RAN OFF THE ROAD AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45 AM ON 10/9/99 AND ROLLED THE TRACTOR TRAILER OVER.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH BOTH FULL AND EMPTY COMPRESSED GAS CYLINDERS.  ALL CYLINDERS WERE INDIVIDUALLY CHECKED FOR DAMAGE AND LEAKS.  ONE 75 LB CARBON DIOXIDE COMPRESSED GAS CYLINDERS WAS FOUND WITH FROST ON THE SAFETY ASSEMBLY WHICH INDICATED A VERY SMALL LEAK. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS LEAK WAS NOT CAUSED BY THE ACCIDENT BECAUSE THE PROTECTIVE STEEL CAP THAT COVERS THE VALVE WAS NOT DAMAGED.  ALSO THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE VALVE, INDICATING THAT THE CYLINDER SAFETY ASSEMBLY COULD HAVE POSSIBLY BEEN LEAKING SINCE LAST BEING RECHARGED WITH CARBON DIOXIDE.  FOLLOWING THE COMPRESSED GAS INDUSTRY PROCEDURES FOR LEAKING CYLINDERS.  THE CARBON DIOXIDE GAS WAS VENTED TO THE ATMOSPHERE UNTIL EMPTY BEFORE BEING SHIPPED TO ITS DESTINATION. THIS ACCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED AT TERMINAL SAFETY MEETINGS IN DETAIL. THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED 7 MILES EAST OF BIG SPRING, NE.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS WEST BOUND ON I-80 AT THE 110 MILE MAKER.  THE CO-DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED WITH NO INJURIES.  THE DRIVER WAS WEARING HIS SEAT BELT AND SUSTAINED NO INJURIES.

AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 AM ON OCTOBER 19, TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS OF 37% HYDROCHLORIC ACID (HCL) WERE ACCIDENTALLY PUNCTURED, RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF ACID.  THE DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED WHEN A FORKLIFT OPERATOR WITH AMD'S CHEMICAL DISTRIBUTION DEPARTMENT WAS BEGINNING TO REMOVE A PALLET OF FOUR HCL DRUMS FROM A SEMI TRAILER AT THE 943 BUILDING LOADING DOCK.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR MISJUDGED THE POSITION OF THE FORKS AS HE APPROACHED THE PALLET AND HIT THE BOTTOM OF THE TWO FRONT DRUMS WITH THE FORKS. HCL LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE LOADING RAMP.  THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED IN THE STORM DRAIN INLET OF THE LOADING DOCK.  THIS INLET HAS A CONTROL VALVE TO CONTAIN LIQUIDS IN SUCH AN EVENT; THEREFORE NO HCL WAS RELEASED INTO THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES REPORTED NOR WAS THERE ANY IMPACT TO THE SURROUNDING COMMUNITY AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT OR EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES.

WHILE THE DRIVER WAS AT THE TERMINAL, FREIGHT WAS IN TRAILER 19-7900, LIQUID BEGAN TO LEAK FROM A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER AND CLEANED UP.  DAMAGED DRUM AND PRODUCT USED TO ABSORB THE SPILL WAS ALL PUT INTO A 85 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM AND IS ON SYR DOCK WAITING DISPOSAL.

A DAMAGED ONE-GALLON BOTTLE OF PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE BOTTLE WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS, INC. THE PLASTIC DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF THE TRIMAC DRIVER FAILING TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF THE EQUIPMENT WHILE MANEUVERING IN TRAFFIC ON THE EXIT RAMP.  AN EVASIVE MANEUVER TO MISS ANOTHER VEHICLE CAUSED THE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER TO SURGE.  THIS SURGE CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLLOVER.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE CARGO TANK WITH THE EXCEPTION OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS THAT LEAKED FROM CLEAN OUT CAPS ON THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK.  ALL NECESSARY PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN TO PROTECT THE SCENE DURING THE SUBSEQUENT CLEAN UP OF THE ACCIDENT.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE AND PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED FROM THE CARGO TANK AS WELL AS MATERIALS USED TO CONTAIN IT.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE OVERTURNED CARGO TANK INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK AT THE SCENE.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE UPRIGHTED AS THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE WITHOUT FURTHER NOTICE.  THE TRIMAC DRIVER EMPLOYMENT WITH TRIMAC WAS TERMINATED AS A RESULT ON THE ACCIDENT.  CAUSES OF THE ACCIDENT WERE COMMUNICATED TO ALL DRIVERS VIA A SAFETY BULLETIN AS WELL AS MADE A POINT OF DISCUSSION DURING SAFETY MEETINGS.

THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD 4 COMPARTMENTS OF DIESEL FUEL.  HE INADVERTENTLY FAILED TO RELOCATE THE LOADING ARM FOLLOWING PARTIAL FILLING OF COMPARTMENT #4.  WHEN HE RESUMED FILLING, THINKING HE WAS ALL SET ON THE NEXT COMPARTMENT, THE OVERFILL OCCURRED.  THE TRAILER WAS EQUIPPED WITH A SCULLY LIQUID OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM WHICH INITIATED AUTOMATIC SHUT DOWN WHEN AN OVERFILL OCCURS.UNFORTUNATELY THIS SHUT DOWN IS NOT INSTANTANEOUS AS THERE IS A FEW SECOND DELAY WHILE VALVES CLOSE.  THE RESULT WAS THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL DISCHARGED FROM THE DOME LID OF THE COMPARTMENT AD SPRAYED, OUTSIDE OF CONTAINMENT, AN AREA 4'X10'.  THERE WAS ONLY SUPERFICIAL CONTAMINATION TO THE ROCK ADJACENT TO THE ROCK.  THERE WAS NO SOIL PENETRATION.  THE ROCKS WERE PLACED INSIDE CONTAINED, PRESSURE WASHED AND RETURNED.  WASH WATER AND DIESEL MIX WENT INTO AN OIL/WATER SEPARATOR.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO HAVE SCULLY-PROBE SETTING ADJUSTED LOWER TO ALLOW ADEQUATE TIME FOR PROPER SHUT DOWN SHOULD THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT REOCCUR.

MR. DENNIS JOHNSON, MGR., CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS ADVISED BY UNION PACIFIC MGR. TRAIN OPERATION SAM KEPHART THAT TANK CAR GATX 80634 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MR. JOHNSON CONTACTED CONTRACTOR ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE INC., OF PHOENIX TO RESPOND TO THE UNION PACIFIC TRAIN YARDS IN PHOENIX AND TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO SECURE THE LEAK. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT STAYED ON THE CAR AND THERE WAS NO GROUND CONTAMINATION.

column168: MGR CTS R SLOANE WAS NOTIFIED BY RAMP FORCES AT THE ALBINA YARD OF A LEAKING CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER, APLU 463623 WAS LEAKING A REDISH COLORED LIQUID THAT WAS FUMING WHEN IT HIT THE GROUND. THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH VARIOUS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCLUDING CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS (HYDROCHLORIC ACID). MR SLOANE ADVISED THE RAMP SUPERVISOR TO NOTIFY RMCC , KEEP ALL PERSONNEL AT LEAST 100 FEET FROM THE CONTAINER UNTIL HIS ARRIVAL AND INVESTIGATION. MR SLOANE DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS FROM A 275 GALLON POLY TOTE CONTAINING A HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION. THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A LOOSE OUTLET CAP. MR SLOANE TIGHTENED THE LOOSE CAP AND SPREAD SOME SODA ASH DOWN INSIDE THE CONTAINER AS A NEUTRALIZER TO STABILIZE THE RELEASE. MR SLOANE MADE CONTACT WITH CHRIS DIMITRUCK OF APL AND ADVISED THEM OF THE LEAK. MR DIMITRUCK CONTACTED A LOCAL APPROVED CONTRACTOR TO FINISH STABILIZATION OF THE CONTAINER AND MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: VERN LIBBY SR SPECIAL AGENT HAZ/MAT II, SEATTLE WA WAS NOTIFIED OF CONTAINER APLU 970280 WHICH HAD JUST ARRIVED IN THE ZMNSE 18 1623 HRS, ON SATURDAY 10/23/99 AND APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. HE WAS FURTHER ADVISED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS A MIXED LOAD OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND HAD BEEN LOCATED AS THE SECOND SOUTH CONTAINER IN RAMP 8. INSPECTION OF CONTAINER AND RAILCAR DEVELOPED EVIDENCE THAT THE CONTAINER HAD LEAKED IN ROUTE HOWEVER THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK AT TIME OF INSPECTION, FURTHER LIBBY WAS UNABLE TO DETECT ANY ODOR/VAPOR OR GET A PH READING OF MATERIALS ON RAILCAR NTTX 66073. LIBBY CONTACTED HALDIS FEARM, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES, HAZ/MAT, OAKLAND. HALDIS CONTACTED THE SHIPPER ZEP MANUFACTURING TO OBTAIN THE PROPER MDSD FOR THE PRODUCTS LOADED IN THE CONTAINER. A JOINT DECISION WAS MADE TO ISOLATE THE CONTAINER WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL AND GREG BARTON, ZEP MFG KENT, WA. APLU 970280 WAS OFF LOADED ONA PLASTIC TRAP AND OPENED FOR INTERIOR INSPECTION.IMMEDIATELY IT WAS NOTED THAT A LIQUID HAD LEAKED AS THE PAINT ON THE INTERIOR WALL OF THE CONTAINER WERE PEELING. FURTHER INSPECTION NOTED A 250 GALLON TOTE CONTAINING CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) WAS MISSING ITS CLOSURE CAPS. THE CAP IN GOOD CONDITION WAS FOUND LYING UPSIDE DOWN ON THE FRON T LEFT TOP CORNER OF THE TOTE. IT WAS REPLACED AND SECURED ON THE TOTE. IN COMPANY WITH DALE REIMER, SITE SUPERVISOR, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL WE AGAIN CHECKED THE PH OF THE PRODUCT ON THE RAILCAR NTTX 66073 AND AGAIN NOTHING TO INDICATE AN ACID OR BASE. FOSS CLEANED THE RAILCAR AND PARTIALLY CLEANED THE CONTAINER INVOLVED ACCOUNT GREG BARTON, BRANCH MFG, KENT WA REQUESTED CONTAINER APLU 970280 BE RELEASED AND DELIVERED TO HIS FACILITY, KENT WA SO HIS FORCES COULD WORK THE CONTAINER. A JOINT INSPECTION BY ALL INVOLVED DETERMINED THAT THERE AGAIN WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK. THEREFORE, THE CONTAINER WAS DOUBLE DIAPERED AND SET ON A CHISIS FOR DELIVERY. BARTON CONTRACTED WITH WESTERN PORTS TRANSPORTATION, SEATTLE TO DRAY THE CONTAINER TO HIS FACILITY APPROXIMATELY 1400 HRS. 102499

column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TOM DIPLEY, YERMO CA WAS NOTIFIED OPERATING DEPARTMENT FORCES THAT TANK CAR GATX 93371 WAS LEAKING. INSPECTION BY SAHM DIPLEY FOUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT OUTLET VALVE CAP LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. SECUREMENT OF BOTH ASSEMBLIES STOPPED THE LEAK. RELEASED PRODUCT EVAPORATED. CHRIS YOUNG WAS FURNISHED AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 10211999049.

WHILE BEING OFF LOADED FROM RAILCAR CONTAINER REDZ 23774 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING A PINK,BUBBLING LIQUID ALONG THE "DRIVER SIDE" APPROXIMATELY 15 FEET FROM THE FRONT. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THE PH=0. THE MATERIAL WAS FURTHER FIELD TESTED AND DETERMINED TO BE NON FLAMMABLE AND WATER SOLUBLE. THE MATERIAL DID NOT MEET THE DESCRIPTION OF THE HAZARDOUS ADHESIVE DESCRIBED ON THE SHIPPING PAPERS. THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND UNCONTAMINATED PACKAGES WERE TRANSFERRED TO EMPU 285250. CONTAMINATED PACKAGES WERE OFF LOADED AND PLACED ON AN IMPERMEABLE TARP PENDING DETERMINATION OF CONTAMINATION AND DISPOSAL. THE BOX CONTAINING THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS FOUND 25 FEET DEEP IN THE SHIPMENT. IT WAS ON THE FLOOR ON THE "DRIVER'S SIDE" THE BOX WAS HAND MARKED THIS END UP AND WAS ON ITS D=SIDE. THE BOX WAS OPENED PRIOR TO MOVEMENT. INSIDE THE SECOND BOX WAS THE FAILED PLASTIC CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS ON ITS SIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 EMPTY. BEFORE MOVING THE BOX IT WAS NOTED THERE WAS CORROSIVE STICKER ON ONE SIDE AND THE DETERGENT MANUFACTURES' LABEL ON THE OTHER. THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED ALONG WITH REMAINING CONTAMINATED BOXES. THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED AND PLASTIC LINERS WERE PLACED ON THE FLOOR BEFORE THE SHIPMENT REPOSITIONED. THIS WAS TO PREVENT WATER DAMAGE TO THE REMAINING PACKAGES. THE "JUG WAS FURTHER INSPECTED BY UP AND UPS AND DETERMINED TO HAVE A PINHOLE IN THE TOP TAPED OVER AND THE VALVE WITH A SOCK. THE UNCONTAMINATED PACKAGES IN THE TWO CONTAINERS WERE RELEASED TO UPS AT 9:20PM. UP MANAGERS HANDLING WERE MTO BALANCE AND ENVIRONMENTAL MGR JIM GORLEY.

column168: MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC REGARDING LEAKING TANKCAR AT PROVO UT. MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED AFTER THE FACT AND THE FOLLOWING REPORT IS A RESULT IS A RESULT OF FOLLOW UP WITH PROVO FIRE DEPT. OFFICER JEREMY MILLIT WAS THE OFFICER THAT MADE THE REPAIR.BASED ON HIS COMMENTS IT SOUND LIKE THE EDUCATION VALVE WAS LEAKING, THIS PROBABLY AS A RESULT OF THE WARM TEMPERATURE IN THE AREA THAT DATE. THIS RESULTED IN THE TANK SELF PRESSURING AND CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE EDUCATION VALVE, WHICH WAS APPARENTLY OPEN OR THE PLUG POSSIBLY LOOSE AS WELL. OFFICER MILLIT CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG. MGR RODABOUGH HAD RMCC NOTIFY CHEMTREC AND MAKE A REPORT

VERN LIBBY SR. SPECIAL AGENT HAZ/MAT II SEATTLE WA WAS NOTIFIED BY A.I WHITEMAN, MYO SEATTLE BOXCAR MP 267649 LOCATED ON THE SOUTH END OF YARD 1 (VAN ASSELT) TRACK 406 WAS LEAKING. FURTHER HE ADVISED, HE HAD ONE EMPLOYEE EXPOSED TO VAPORS ONLY. LIBBY OBTAINED BILLING INFORMATION FROM WHITEMAN AND INSPECTED THE BOXCAR, FINDING A VERY SMALL DRIP ON THE RIGHT A ENF CORNER. HE CONTACTED DAVE HAUGE, PLANT SUPERVISOR, PHILLIP ENVIRONMENTAL, (SHIPPER) WHO ASSIGNED 2 EMPLOYEES TO FURTHER ASSIST WITH THE INSPECTION OF THE BOXCAR. SECOND INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE DRIPPING TO BE WATER. HOWEVER LEFT DOOR SEAL TRAILMOBILE 2516442 WAS REMOVED AND DOOR OPENED. NO VISIBLE LEAK NOTED IN DOORWAY. BOXCAR MP 267643 LOADED IN DOORWAY WITH DRUMS AND PALLETS OF SUPER SACKS AND BEHIND BULKHEAD DOORS IN ENDS WITH SAME. A VERY PUNGENT ODOR WAS DETECTED ALL AROUND THIS BOXCAR. BOXCAR DOOR CLOSED AND BOXCAR RETURNED TO THE SHIPPERS FACILITY TO BE UNLOADED TO DETERMINE IF ANY OF THE DRUMS FLAMMABLE LIQUID WERE LEAKING. PHILLIP ENVIRONMENTAL DID UNLOAD BOXCAR MP 267643 FINDING NO LEAK. HOWEVER SEVERAL OF THE SUPER SACKS WERE NOTED WITH RAIN WATER ON THEIR TOPS. A RESULT OF BEING STORED OUTSIDE PRIOR TO SHIPMENT. BILL STREETY SR MYO SEATTLE WA IDENTIFIED THE EXPOSED EMPLOYEE AS KEVIN R DURY A SWITCHMAN. STREEY ADVISED DURY WAS TAKEN TO PROVIDENCE HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR HEADACHE AND RELEASED.

column168: MITCH DUGGER ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER COLTON CALIFORNIA REPORTED TO MR M JOHNSON OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY THAT HE FOUND RAILROAD TANKCAR CPDX 283197 IN TRACK 208, COLTON RECEIVING YARD LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV). THE CAR WAS RESIDUE EMPTY WITH A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM FROM THE SRV. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND MADE NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER. CHERVON PRODUCTS WAS CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC WHO IN TURN CONTACTED MR JOHNSON. AFTER FOUR DIFFERENT CONTACTS WITH CHEVRON PERSONNEL THE CAR WAS MOVED AND ISOLATED IN AN AREA FROM BUSINESS AND EMPLOYEES UNTIL CHEVRON COULD ARRANGE REPAIRS. ON THE FOLLOWING DAY ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH GATX REPAIR FACILITY AT COLTON TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE CAR. GATX PERSONNEL FOUND THAT THE SRV WAS CORRODED AND RUSTED I THE POSITION AND THE VACUUM BRAKER VALVE WAS INOPERABLE. BOTH VALVE WERE REPLACED BY GATX AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL TRANSPORTATION. DUE TO THE EVENTS THAT TOOK PLACE WITH THIS INCIDENT, COMPLETE DETAILS ARE COVERED IN ATTACHED UNION PACIFIC R.M.C.C REPORT NUMBER 1999-10-19-021JDC. CHEVRON PRODUCTS WAS SHOWN AS OWNER OF THE PRODUCT AND CAR.

AB8499, SHIPPER: CORE LABORATORIES, AWB# LGB1963962022 TGC.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  00:27 ON 10/13/99 AN ADOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 206 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS MARTIN CLINE AND PAUL SCHMIDT DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE TO THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS:  COMPRESSED GASES, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S., UN1954, DOT-E-8249 NO DOT LABEL REQUIRED, FLAMMABLE GAS LABEL, CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY LABEL, ORIENTATION ARROWS AND CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4 STEEL CYLINDERS, ONE LARGE CYLINDER AND 3 SMALL CYLINDERS.  THE CYLINDERS WERE SWAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP WITH STYROFOAM PACKING PEANUTS AROUND EACH CYLINDER.  EACH CYLINDER HAS 2 SCREW TYPE VALVES WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE VALVES.  APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF THE COMPRESSED GAS LEAKED FROM THE LARGE CYLINDER.  THE 3 SMALL CYLINDER DID NOT LEAK.  THEY SECURED THE VALVES ON THE LARGE CYLINDER, RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT INTO A FIBREBOARD BOX.  ALL OUTER BOX MARKINGS, LABELS AND CERTIFICATION WERE DUPLICATED ON THE NEW OUTER BOX BEFORE THE SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED TO DESTINATION.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE WHO CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE ODOR EMITTING FROM THE SHIPMENT.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND RETURNED TO HIS NORMAL WORK AREA.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THE ODOR WAS VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 00:42.

AB8599, SHIPPER DELTA FIBERGLASS, AWB#SLC1838410685NLA.  THIS IS A PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. 10-13-99, 02:27 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT:  ABX AIR INC.M 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177, PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND MIRANDA SOUTH DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A RED "C" CONTAINER CONTAINING A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THE BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS:  RESIN SOLUTION, UN1866, CLASS 3 LABEL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS. CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WAS ATTACHED TO THE BOX.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 2 - 1 GALLON METAL CANS WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES WITH PLASTIC SEAL BANDS AROUND THE CLOSURES, BOTH PACKED WITH STYROFOAM END CAPS ON THE TOP AND BOTTOM OF EACH CAN, MESH FABRIC BETWEEN THE CANS AND STYROFOAM PACKAGING PEANUTE.  THERE WAS VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE TOP OF ONE OF THE CANS.  THE LEAKEAGE CAUSED THE STYROFOAM AND CAP ON THE TOP OF THE CAN TO MELT.  THEY INSPECTED THE CLOSURE ON THIS CAN, FOUND IT TO BE UNSECURE CAUSEIN THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF THE RESIN SOLUTION.  THEY ALSO FOUND THIS METAL CAN TO BE CRUSHED ON ONE SIDE WHERE THE SIDE OF THE CAN MEETS THE CLOSURE.  THEY SECURED THE CLOSURE, REPLACED THE METAL CANS BACK INTO THE FIBREBOARD BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT  INSIDE A RECOVERY DURM FOR TRANSPORT ON TO DESTINATION.  ALL MARKINGS, LABELS AND CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WRE DUPLICATED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE RECOVERY DRUM BEFORE TRANSPORT.  THE "C" CONTAINER WAS VENTILATED BEFORE IT WAS PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR, SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT CAUSED THE ODOR AND RETURNED TO HER  NORMAL WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 02:47

PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIANS JEFFERY KIDDER AND CHRISTOPHER CHOPPA DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS:  ACETONE, UN1090, CLASS 3 LABEL AND ORIENTATION ARROWS, WITH CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS AND A PACKING SLIP. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR KEN HAAG AND PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN CECILLIA HICKEY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. (ETHANOL, ISOPROPANOL), CLASS 3 LABEL, CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY LABEL, ORIENTATION ARROWS AND CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4-1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES. column42: CARTRIDGES FOR WEAPONS, INERT PROJECTILE OR CARTRIDGES, SMALL ARMS
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN DAMAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LOADED ABROAD AN INBOUND TRUCK ROUTE.  APPARENTLY OTHER HEAVIER PACKAGES HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF THE OUTER CONTAINER EFFECTIVELY CRUSHING THE OUTER BOX AND ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE INNER UNITS CONTAINING THE CARTRIDGES.  THE CARTRIDGES WERE RETRIEVED, PUT BACK IN THEIR INNER UNITS AND PUT BACK INTO THE OUTERMOST PACKAGE.  AFTER ALL THE CARTRIDGE BOXES WERE ACCOUNTED FOR THE SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED AND FORWARDED ON TO THE RECIPIENT FOR DELIVERY.

ON OCTOBER 21, 1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1431 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED METHYL MERCAPTAN, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHILE TRAVELING THROUGH LEESVILLE, LOUISIANA ON THE MAIN LINE TRACK. THE LEAK WAS OBSERVED BY A KCS EMPLOYEE, WORKING IN THE RAIL YARD, WHO WAS ALLEGEDLY EXPOSED TO THIS MATERIAL. THE EMPLOYEE WAS HOSPITALIZED ONE WEEK LATER, ALLEGING INJURY CAUSED FROM THE EXPOSURE. EMPLOYEE INJURY STATUS MAY BE SECURED FROM KCS' KEVIN MCINTOSH AT (816)9831661. AFTER LEARNING OF THE INCIDENT, KCS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND PROVIDED FOR IN-FIELD REPAIR TO A DEFECTIVE VAPOR VALVE AND LIQUID VALVE PACKING. ONCE SHIPPER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETE, THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FINAL DESTINATION.

THE CONTENTS WERE EXACTLY THE SAME 4-1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE. THIS 2 PIECE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE ONE RECOVERY DRUM, ALL MARKINGS LABELS AND CERTIFICATIONS WERE DUPLICATED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE DRUM BEFORE TRANSPORT ON TO DESTINATION. TOTAL SPILL CLEAN UP FOR THIS SHIPMENT 54 MINUTES.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER MITCH DUGGER, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE COLTON YARD.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND OBSERVED THE ABOVE TANK CAR DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM SUMP AT A RATE OF ONE DROP EVERY 5 TO 10 SECONDS. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE WELDS WHERE THE SUMP IS ATTACHED TO THE BELLY OF THE TANK CAR.  THIS CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH BOTTOM SKID PROTECTION, WHICH RESTRICTED ACCESS TO THE WELDS.  A MAKE SHIFT PLATFORM WAS ATTACHED TO THE UNDERSIDE OF THE CAR WHICH WAS USED TO CRADLE A CONTAMINANT POOL AND CAPTURE THE DRIPPING PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO THE GATX REPAIR SHOP, WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED FOR THE EVENING OVER A CONTAMINANT PIT.  THE AFFECTED TRACKAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED UTILIZING AGRICULTURAL LIME.  THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE CAR WAS OPENED TO INSPECT THE LINING AND IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE FULLY LOADED.  ALL OF THE MOVEMENT PAPER WORK INDICATED THIS CAR WAS MOVING AS AN EMPTY. CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, HILLS BROTHERS, DEVELOPED THE CAR HAD BEEN RELEASED IN ERROR PRIOR TO UNLOADING.  CONTACT WAS THEN MADE WITH THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER, MAGCORP, WHO ARRANGED TO HAVE THE PRODUCT REMOVED FROM THE CAR THROUGH A LOCAL DISTRIBUTOR.  MAGCORP IS WORKING WITH GATX TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE RECEIVING YARD FOREMAN, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING UNUSUAL ODORS.  THE CARMEN WERE INSPECTING AN INBOUND TRAIN ON YARD TRACK 807 WHEN THEY NOTICED SOME ODORS NEAR THE CENTER AREA OF THE TRAIN.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD, INSPECTED SEVERAL TANK CARS IN THE AREA OF THE TRAIN THE CARMEN IDENTIFIED, AND FOUND THE ABOVE TANK CAR EMITTING A SLIGHT VAPOR FROM AROUND THE BASE MOUNTING PLATE OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, A STANDARD MIDLAND 75 POUND SRV, WAS MOUNTED OUTSIDE THE WORK PLATFORM AREA, ON THE 'A' END OF THE TANK CAR.  IN COMPANY WITH ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER MITCH DUGGER, THE VAPOR PRESSURE WITHIN THE CAR WAS BLED OFF, WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR RELEASE AT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV).  THE SRV WAS REMOVED, AND IT WAS NOTED THAT THE GASKET MATERIAL APPEARED TO BE WORN DOWN ON ONE SIDE.  IT APPEARS THAT THE 4 BOLTS ON ONE SIDE OF THE SRV HAD BEEN OVER TIGHTENED, CAUSING THE GASKET TO DEFORM AND FLATTEN OUT.  AS A SUITABLE REPLACEMENT GASKET WAS NOT AVAILABLE, A TEMPORARY GASKET MADE FROM GORTEX SEALANT WAS INSTALLED.  ONCE THE SRV WAS BOLTED BACK IN PLACE, THE SOURCE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE CEASED.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH A SHIPPER, WHO WAS ADVISED THE CAR WOULD BE PLACED ON HOLD UNTIL A PROPER REPLACEMENT GASKET COULD BE INSTALLED.  THE SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH GATX MOBIL REPAIR SERVICE TO REPACE THE SRV GASKET, WHICH WAS COMPLETED ON 10/07/99.  ONCE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS WERE MADE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

SUPERVISOR KRIS COOL, FIRST TO RESPOND.  I LATER RESPONDED WITH ALL PPE TO UPPER BLOOMINGTON SLIDE.  IDENTIFIED LEAKER AS A CORROSIVE BY DIAMOND LABEL AND 5-PART FORM.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE I PH TESTED TO A 2, NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER AND RETESTED AT 7. MR, HICKEN WAS ON HIS WAY TO DELIVER A LOAD OF PROPANE TO A CUSTOMER ACCOUNT IN MILFORD VALLEY, A PIG FARM.  AT OR AROUND 2:20 PM PTI DISPATCHER MARTY REYNA RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. HICKENS STATING THAT HIS RIG WAS OVER ON ITS SIDE AND HE WAS USING A PASSERSBY CELL PHONE TO MAKE THIS CALL.  PTI DISPATCHER REYNA WAS ABLE TO VERBALLY CONFIRM THAT MR. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING THE ABOVE CONTAINER LEAKING IN THE FACILITY LOCATED IN THE GREEN ROW SPACE 574. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LOCATION AND OBSERVED A THICK BROWN LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE NOSE OF THE 40 FOOT CONTAINER AND A PUDDLE OF THE LIQUID APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS HAD ACCUMULATED ON THE PAVEMENT. THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED AND IT WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR CONTAINMENT AND INSPECTION. SEAL SEALED 31829 WAS REMOVED AND THE REAR DOORS OPENED TO EXPOSE THE LADING. NUMEROUS PICES OF 2X4 LUMBER WERE NOTED ATTACHED TO VARIOUS PIECES OF LUMBER THAT HAD BEEN  PLACED HORIZONTALLY ACROSS THE MIXED LADING. THE 2X4 HAD BEEN NAILED TO THE HORIZONTAL PIECES AND EXTENDED TO THE ROOF LINE OF THE CONTAINENR. IT WAS NOT DETERMINED EXACTLY WHAT THE SHIPPERS INTENT WAS IN UTILIZING THIS LUMBER. THERE WAS NO FORM OF BLOCKING OR BRACING OBSERVED TO OTHER WISE SECURES THE LADING. 2 PALLETS CONTAINING 50 POUNDS BAGS OF NON REGULATED SODIUM TRIPOLYPHOSPHATE WERE SCATTERED ACROSS THE REAR OF THE LADING ACCOUNT THE STRECH WRAP HAD FAILED TO HOLD THEM IN PLACE. NUMEROUS BAGS HAD TORN OPEN AND THE POWDER WAS COVERING THE FLOOR AND OTHER FREIGHT. 1 PALLET ON THE RIGHT SIDE AT THE DOOR CONTAINED 24 CARTONS OF INKJET PRINTER CARTIDGES. THE CARTON HAD TOPPLED DUE TO THE STRECH WRAP FAILING. THESE CARTONS WERE MARKED AS FLAMMABLE , HOWEVER THEY DID NOT APPEAR ON THE BILLING INFORMATION AS BEING PART OF THE HAZARDOUS LADING. FURTHER INTO THE CONTAINER NUMEROUS DRUMS OF  LUBRIZOL A NON REGULATED LUBRICANT WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM DAMAGED ROLLING HOOPS OR BOTTOM CHIMES. THE ROLLING HOOP DAMAGED WAS A RESULT OF THE DRUMS RUBBING AGAINST ADJACENT DRUMS AND THE BOTTOMCHIME DAMAGED WAS A RESULT OF RUBBING OR ABRASION OF THE CHIME CONTACTING FLOOR SCREWS THAT HAD BACKED OUT. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATLEY 130 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD ESCAPE FROM 11 DAMAGED DRUMS OF THIS PRODUCT. FURTHER INTO THE LADING 4 EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS OF ACETIC WERE LOCATED. THE DRUMS HAD SOME MINOR WEAR ONTHE ROLLING HOOPS HOWEVER WERE INTACTDID NOT LEAK AND WERE DEEMED FIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT. THIS COMMODITY WAS PLACARDED CORRISVIE AND DID NOT APPEAR ON THE BILLING INFORMATION AS BEING PART OF THE HAZARDOUS LADING. FURTHER INTO THE LOAD 1 DRUM OF BAKER PETROLITE DEMULSOFOER A FLAAMABLE LIQUID WAS LOCATED WITH DAMAGED TO THE TOP ROLLING HOOP. THE DAMAGED RESULT FROM ABRASION WITH AN ADJACENT DRUM. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 5 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THIS DRUM. BOTH OF THESE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A OVER PACK FOR SECURMENT. OF THE LISTED 33 DRUMS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES ONLY 8 WERE DEEMED FIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT. THE REMIANING DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVER PACKS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR REQUEST. ONCE THE CONTAINER FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF RESIDUE ALL OF THE REMAINING LADING WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGNAL CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO T

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF LONG BEACH CA. MANAGER COOPER TO THE ICTF AND INSPECTED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN EAST ROADWAY SPACE 77. WHILE THERE WAS NO PHYSICAL EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT LEAKING THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR BEING EMITTED FROM THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMERS DOCK DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. AS THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION IT WAS DECIDED TO LET THE CONTAINER SET UNTIL THE FOLLOWING MORNING. THE FOLLOWING MORNING CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MOL INTERMODAL, THE RAILROADS SHIPPER OF RECORD WHO PROVIDED A CONTACT FOR THE SHIPPER OF THE LANDING. INSPECTION OF THE LADING DEVELOPED THE CONTENTS TO BE OPEN TOP DRUMS DOUBLE STACKED WITHIN THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER. THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS NOT TO STANDARD AND THE DRUMS WERE NOT RISERED. SEVERAL OF  OF THE VISIBLE DRUMS ON TOP LAYER HAD POPPED UP AND WERE RESTING ON THE RING TOPS OF THE ADJACENT DRUMS. THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE DESCREPNCIES AND NOTED ODORS. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CONTENTS REMOVED AND INSPECTED. UPON REMOVING THE DRUMS A SINGLE  DRUM ON THE FLOOR IN NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, 2ND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL WAS FOUND TO HAVE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTOM CHIME. THE DRUM HAD BEEN SET ON A NAIL LOCATED IN THE FLOOR DURING THE LOADING PROCESS WHICH DAMAGED THE CHIME AND ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO WEEP FROM THE DRUM DURING TRANSIT. ADDITIONAL NAILS WERE LOCATED IN THE FLOORING DURING THE REMOVAL PROCESS BUT THE DRUMS DID NOT NOT CONTACT THE NAILS TO POINT WHERE THE DRUMS WERE NOT DAMAGED FROM CONTACT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECURMENT. THIS DRUMS WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR REQUEST. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER PROPERLY RISERED AND BLOCKED AND BRACED. ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED IT WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE LOADED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARGO (NURSE) TANK WAS BEING TOWED BY A PICKUP TRUCK ON A PAVED HIGHWAY (RTE 225) EAST OF SULLY.  AS THE PICKUP AND TOWED NURSE TANK CRESTED A HILL, THE DRIVER OBSERVED A VEHICLE IMMEDIATELY IN FRONT OF HIM WAITING AN OPPORTUNITY TO TURN LEFT AS SOON AS THE APPROACHING TRAFFIC CLEARED.  THE DRIVER OF THE PICKUP APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND SWERVED TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID A REAR END COLLISION.  UPON DOING SO, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO CONTROL THE CARGO TANK.  THE TANK BEGAN TO FISHTAIL.  THE HITCH PIN HOLDING TO CARGO TANK TO THE PICKUP FAILED.  THE CARGO TANK EXITED THE HIGHWAY TO THE RIGHT, ENTERED A ROADWAY DITCH, PASSED THROUGH A PASTURE FENCE AND OVERTURNED, UPON IMPACT THE TRANSFER VALVES ON TOP OF THE CARGO TANK WERE COMPROMISED THEREBY ALLOWING THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IN THE TANK TO ESCAPE.  COMPANY AND OTHER OFFICIALS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.
